Intent classification is a natural language processing (NLP) task that involves identifying the intention or purpose behind a given text input, such as a sentence or a phrase. The goal is to classify the input into one of several pre-defined categories, each of which represents a specific intent.

Intent classification is a key component of many NLP applications, including chatbots, virtual assistants, and customer service systems. By accurately identifying the intent of the user's input, these systems can provide appropriate responses and actions.

There are several approaches to intent classification, including rule-based systems, machine learning models, and deep learning models. Machine learning and deep learning models, in particular, have become popular due to their ability to learn from large amounts of data and improve their accuracy over time. These models typically require labeled training data, which consists of text inputs and their corresponding intent labels, to learn the patterns and relationships between different inputs and intents. Once trained, the model can classify new inputs into the appropriate intent category with a high degree of accuracy.

